# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1876 Chicago White Stockings season** was the fifth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the first in the National League and the third at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1876-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings, as one of the founding members of the new National League, won the NL's initial championship during this season with a record of 52–14.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The **1878 Boston Red Caps season** was the eighth season of the franchise.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1878-boston-red-caps-season] The Red Caps won their second straight National League pennant.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1879-providence-grays-season] The **1879 Providence Grays** won the National League title in only their second season in the league.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1880 Chicago White Stockings season** was the ninth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the fifth in the National League and the third at Lakefront Park.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1880-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 67–17.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1881 Chicago White Stockings season** was the tenth season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the sixth in the National League and the fourth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1881-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 56–28.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1882 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 11th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the seventh in the National League and the fifth at Lakefront Park.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1882-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings won the National League championship with a record of 55–29, 3 games ahead of the second place Providence Grays.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] The **1941 Brooklyn Dodgers**, led by manager Leo Durocher, won their first pennant in 21 years, edging the St.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] They went on to lose to the New York Yankees in the World Series.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] In The New Bill James Historical Baseball Abstract, this team was referenced as one of "The Greatest Teams That Never Was", due to the quality of its starting lineup.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] Dolph Camilli was the slugging star with 34 home runs and 120 RBI.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] He was voted the National League's Most Valuable Player.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] Pete Reiser, a 22-year-old rookie, led the league in batting average, slugging percentage, and runs scored.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] Other regulars included Hall of Famers Billy Herman, Joe Medwick, Pee Wee Reese, and Dixie Walker.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] Not surprisingly, the Dodgers scored the most runs of any NL team (800).
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] The pitching staff featured a pair of 22-game winners, Kirby Higbe and Whitlow Wyatt, having their best pro seasons.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] On July 1, the Dodgers played the Phillies in Brooklyn; the game was televised by WNBT in New York (now WNBC), making the contest the first program aired by a commercial TV station in the United States.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] Although the Dodgers would later win the pennant and the Phillies would finish in last place in the NL, Philadelphia won the game 6–4, in 10 innings.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] Note: Hugh Casey was team leader in saves with 7.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] The **1941 World Series** matched the New York Yankees against the Dodgers, with the Yankees winning in five games to capture their fifth title in six years, and their ninth overall.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] The name "Subway Series" arose for a World Series played between two New York City teams.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] The series was punctuated by the Dodgers' Mickey Owen's dropped third strike of a sharply breaking curveball (a suspected spitball) pitched by Hugh Casey to Tommy Henrich in the 9th inning of Game 4.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] The play led to a Yankees rally and brought them one win away from another championship.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] The Yankees were back after a one-year hiatus, having won thirteen (13) of their last fourteen (14) Series games and twenty-eight (28) of their last thirty-one (31) games in the World Series.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] This was the first Subway Series between the Brooklyn Dodgers and New York Yankees, who had already faced the crosstown New York Giants five times, and the Series was now 1–0 in favor of the Bronx Bombers.
[src:1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season/1941-brooklyn-dodgers-season] These two teams would meet a total of seven (7) times from 1941 to 1956 – the Dodgers' only victory coming in 1955.
